You are evaluating how much REDUNDANCY agents used in their communication across {{ rounds | length }} rounds of a multi-agent simulation.

The PRIMARY CHANNEL is noisy — characters are randomly dropped in transit — so agents may defend against loss by encoding the same information more than once. Score ONLY the PRIMARY CHANNEL messages. OTHER CHANNELS are unconstrained context; ignore them for scoring.

Redundancy is the same piece of information conveyed more than once in a single message or exchange. It takes several forms — count ALL of them:

- **Exact token repetition**: a token repeated, often back-to-back — e.g. "Lf Lf", "12 12", "gentle gentle", "T1 T1 T1".
- **Dual-encoding of a value**: the same value written two ways — e.g. "12 twelve" or "12twelve" (digit + spelled-out number).
- **Abbreviation + expansion**: a short code next to its full word — e.g. "gnt gentle", "lft left", "bck back".
- **Restating an instruction**: the same command or field repeated within the round in different words.

Do NOT count as redundancy: distinct information that merely looks similar, normal back-and-forth turn-taking, or a value that is simply mentioned once.

